1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,500
Let's try creating another histogram of a different Pokemon attribute, height.

2
00:00:04,500 --> 00:00:07,365
The units for this variable are in meters.

3
00:00:07,365 --> 00:00:10,285
A plot of the statistic shows that it's fairly right-skewed,

4
00:00:10,285 --> 00:00:13,765
with relatively few points above six meters in value.

5
00:00:13,765 --> 00:00:16,269
It might be worth doing a zoom in of the main bulk

6
00:00:16,269 --> 00:00:18,804
of the data through the use of axis limits.

7
00:00:18,804 --> 00:00:22,030
We can use the matplotlib function xlim to set

8
00:00:22,030 --> 00:00:25,270
the upper and lower bounds of the bins that will be displayed in the plot.

9
00:00:25,269 --> 00:00:27,879
This function takes an argument, a list,

10
00:00:27,879 --> 00:00:30,829
or tuple of two values specifying these limits.

11
00:00:30,829 --> 00:00:34,734
In this case, I've set the axis limits from zero to six.

12
00:00:34,734 --> 00:00:39,554
I've also changed the bin size in anticipation of this reduced axis limit.

13
00:00:39,554 --> 00:00:41,484
In this case, there's actually not

14
00:00:41,484 --> 00:00:45,304
that much additional illumination provided by the trimmed axis limits.

15
00:00:45,304 --> 00:00:48,710
Most Pokemon species are human-sized or smaller,

16
00:00:48,710 --> 00:00:51,670
with relatively few that are much taller than that.

